[![](https://globalvoices.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Edo-
Censura-1-800x450.jpg)](https://www.facebook.com/edoilustrado/photos/p.10158414209795632/10158414209795632/?type=1&theater)

Detail of illustrator Eduardo Sanabria's image alluding to media censorship
and self-censorship in Venezuela. Used with permission.

Amid widespread protests in response to Venezuela's social, political and
economic crises, state control over information has reached new heights.

In June 2018, Venezuelans have seen online newspapers, pornography sites, and
the Tor network blocked, in what appears to be the latest move in an ever-
evolving strategy to limit access to information for the general public.

The road has been [long and
steady.](https://advox.globalvoices.org/2016/09/08/detention-of-news-site-
director-raises-concerns-for-venezuelas-freedom-of-speech/) What began with
limitations on access to [radio and television
spectrum](https://www.hrw.org/es/report/2008/09/18/una-decada-de-
chavez/intolerancia-politica-y-oportunidades-perdidas-para-el) during the
administration of deceased former president Hugo Chávez has since expanded,
under president Nicolás Maduro, with many once-privately run broadcast and
press outlets having transitioned toward a model wherein [the state has either
explicit or soft power](https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-19649652)
over editorial and commercial activities.

Also, in 2017, Venezuela's National Constituent Assembly (ANC) – which had
[assumed all legislative powers](https://globalvoices.org/2017/03/31/for-many-
venezuelans-self-inflicted-coup-spells-the-end-of-their-countrys-democracy/)
that had previously come under the purview of the National Legislative
Assembly- [passed a controversial
law](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-08/venezuela-passes-anti-
hate-law-threatening-media-censorship) that would [regulate social
media](https://globalvoices.org/2017/08/25/venezuelan-government-wants-to-
regulate-hatred-on-social-media/) and sanction or pull out of the air any
outlet “promoting hate”. The measure seemed to had been already in practice,
given the cases of [people that have been put behind bars because of a
tweet](https://advox.globalvoices.org/2015/11/10/in-venezuela-140-characters-
can-land-you-in-jail/).

Since 2014, the ongoing crisis has generated chronic shortages of basic goods
and services, [like paper](https://www.pri.org/stories/2013-09-05/venezuelas-
press-dying-paper-shortage),
[electricity](https://advox.globalvoices.org/2016/06/08/in-venezuela-
electrical-shortages-limit-basic-communication-and-free-expression/) and
[broadband](https://ipysvenezuela.org/2018/05/08/internet-surfing-at-its-
minimum-situation-of-internet-in-venezuela/) internet. These shortages
combined with political efforts to limit public access to information and news
have created a tense and highly controlled landscape for communication and the
sharing of information.

### **Newspapers are moving online…and then they're being blocked**

With the cost of newsprint rising rapidly and the paper itself almost non-
existent, local newspapers (especially those critical of the government) [were
forced to close down or move online](https://cpj.org/blog/2017/12/end-of-the-
print-run-for-venezuelas-regional-press.php), where they had no guarantee of
maintaining an audience. In early 2018, one journalist tweeted:  

> Reportan que el portal de El Nacional fue bloqueado en varios lugares de
> Venezuela. [pic.twitter.com/q0yqUHZ8Ij](https://t.co/q0yqUHZ8Ij)
>
> — Maibort Petit (@maibortpetit) [January 15,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/maibortpetit/status/952937199493959680?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> There are reports of newspaper El Nacional being blocked in many areas of
> Venezuela

> Observo que hoy está bloqueado en mi computadora el acceso a El Nacional, La
> Patilla y otros sitios venezolanos “molestos” para la dictadura. ¿Otros
> tienen el mismo problema? Para hacer las denuncias del casos.
>
> — TamaraAdrian (@TamaraAdrian) [January 15,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/TamaraAdrian/status/953027869747400707?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> I'm seeing now that [daily newspapers] El Nacional, La Patilla and other
> “annoying” sites for the dictatorship are blocked in my computer. Are others
> having the same problem? We should report the cases.

Months later, in early June, El Nacional, one of the most important newspapers
in the country, was reported to be blocked again both by journalists on
Twitter and in [other news
outlets](https://www.lanacion.com.ar/2142749-venezuela-uno-de-los-diarios-mas-
leidos-denuncio-haber-sido-bloqueado-por-una-empresa-de-telecomunicaciones):

> Así está El Nacional en servidores cantv: Bloqueado
> [pic.twitter.com/PeGyfuXgPM](https://t.co/PeGyfuXgPM)
>
> — Beatriz Adrián (@Beadrian) [June 8,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/Beadrian/status/1005108125437812736?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> This how El Nacional looks like in CANTV (the most important Internet
> provider) servers

### ‘It's not about porn, it's about blocking’

Espacio Público, an organization defending free speech and access to
information [reported through their Twitter
account](https://twitter.com/espaciopublico/status/1008052570584207360?s=19)
that public internet provider CANTV had blocked the access to sites with
sexual content like Pornhub and Youporn.

The measure caught the attention of the public and the press,
[inside](http://www.2001.com.ve/en-la-agenda/188608/cantv-bloquea-el-acceso-a-
algunas-paginas-pornograficas-en-venezuela.html) and [outside the
country](https://www.elespectador.com/noticias/el-mundo/en-venezuela-tambien-
bloquean-la-pornografia-articulo-795260). Media workers shared their
impressions of [authoritarian views](https://medium.com/@burrozombi/venezuela-
se-queda-sin-porno-932b2cceb1a5) on morals and decency:

> La pregunta a hacerse aquí es, ¿cómo es que se llegó a este punto?
> Cualquiera por lógica diría que el chavismo es un régimen que lento pero
> seguro, se mete con todos los sectores de la sociedad. Así no sean
> numerosos, los quita del camino para completar su dominación social.

> The question here is: how did we get to this point? Anyone being logical
> would say that chavismo is a system that, slowly but surely, meddles with
> every aspect of society. Even if some of these aspects are not big in
> number, they put them away to complete their social domination.

Other users have been quick to analyze the actual reach of the move and its
close link with online censorship, a concern present[ not only in
Venezuela](https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jan/03/david-
cameron-internet-porn-filter-censorship-creep):

> El problema central que yo veo, no es solo el bloqueo a páginas
> pronográficas, que de por sí ya es una catástrofe, sino que este bloqueo se
> va a extender a otras páginas.
>
> ¿Qué ganaban bloqueando páginas porno? ensayar el bloqueo a otras páginas,
> de repente la próxima es youtube.
>
> — Su Alteza Real (@rhL_93) [June 16,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/rhL_93/status/1008070955107831810?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> The problem here is not the fact that they're blocking porn webpages -which
> is already a disaster-, the problem es that it will go further to other
> pages. What do they gain from blocking porn webpages? Try blocking pages,
> maybe Youtube will come next.

However, other users suspect that is neither about porn, nor censorship. For
them, the problem is bandwidth, and the impossibility of paying for it:

> El bloqueo de
> [#CANTV](https://twitter.com/hashtag/CANTV?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw) a
> páginas web de
> [#porno](https://twitter.com/hashtag/porno?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw), no
> es por mojigatería, no es porque el gobierno quiera proteger a los niños. Es
> básicamente porque
> [#Venezuela](https://twitter.com/hashtag/Venezuela?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> no tiene dinero para pagar el ancho de banda que se consume en esas páginas
> cobrando $0.30 por una conexión de internet.
>
> — Maxx (@simbiosisgroup) [June 17,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/simbiosisgroup/status/1008340416234770433?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> CANTV's [Venezuela's national internet and phone provider] blockade to porn
> webpages is not about being prudish, or about the government wanting to
> protect the children. It's basically because Venezuela doesn't have money to
> pay the for bandwidth that those pages need charging $0.30 for an internet
> connection.

### What are the alternatives? Perhaps Tor can help… or not

Tor, the free software used to surf the web anonymously that has allowed many
to use internet safely has also been blocked, according to different reports
online.

The blockages of different nodes in the Tor network seems to be happening
intermittently, and are thus not completely effective. Nevertheless,
organizations like Acceso Libre or VE Sin filtro [have
confirmed](https://twitter.com/vesinfiltro/status/1009596837911826432) Tor
being blocked and proposed solutions to curb the limitations:

> Podemos confirmar Tor está bloqueado (en conexión directa)
> [@torproject](https://twitter.com/torproject?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw), se puede
> usar con el bridge (pluggable transport) Meek
> [#keepiton](https://twitter.com/hashtag/keepiton?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> [#bloqueos](https://twitter.com/hashtag/bloqueos?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> [#internetVE](https://twitter.com/hashtag/internetVE?src=hash&ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)
> [pic.twitter.com/AOm2Ov8t60](https://t.co/AOm2Ov8t60)
>
> — VE sin Filtro (@vesinfiltro) [June 20,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/vesinfiltro/status/1009516878820265984?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> We can confirm Tor as blocked (in direct connection). You can use
> @torproject with the bridge (pluggable transport).

> Se reportan bloqueos a la red de
> [@torproject](https://twitter.com/torproject?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw) en
> Venezuela. Aquí, cómo sortear la censura al configurar Tor para usar
> puentes: [pic.twitter.com/9K2egK6XsK](https://t.co/9K2egK6XsK)
>
> — Acceso Libre (@AccesoLibreRed) [June 20,
> 2018](https://twitter.com/AccesoLibreRed/status/1009423060288659456?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw)

> Blocks to @torproject network are being reported in Venezuela. Here's how
> you can bend it configuring Tor to use bridges.

Given the context and the background, the prognosis for freedom of speech and
access of information in the country looks grim. Many Venezuelans are
wondering which media space or communication tool will be censored next…and
what they can do to outsmart the government's efforts.

